item.title: Any Engineers? mathematicians?
item.dc:creator: @SETO SETO
item.description:
@SETO wrote:

[quote=“la­wl, post:16, topic:339654”][quote author=SETO link=topic=436032.msg3202988#msg3202988 date=1273513713]

out of curiosity, cause i remember not long ago most of us here we in high school, just curious where everyone ended up.

i am going to be on my third year as chemical engineering student, 2 more years with a whole year of co-op. (#1 engineering school in canada :p)

by the way i gota a question about American collages/university

commonly in Canada if you were to attend collage means you going to be a technician rather than an engineer, but in the states collages and university are at the same level? cause most ppl are going to collages.

here in Canada universities are though of being a higher standard than collages.

well most look down on collages.

waterloo? ill be there next year

UOFT :p, waterloo is known for its co-op. well due to recessions alot of first years are doing voluntary co-op cause not much ppl are hiring.

i like uoft better whats better than to have a class in a 100+ years old buildings. and Gothic architecture.
[/quote]
waterloo is known for engineering, its far better than uoft. uoft is considered the best in canada overall because its the oldest[/quote]

lol not because its oldest, waterloo is only known for its co-op program, what makes uoft better? it supports and mainly focus it self on research, also uoft got something called PEY, that means you get to work 12-16 months cts, not 4 months back and forth, that means where ever you work you’d be there for year+ and they would trust you on bigger projects, if you go back and forth for 4 months you wouldn’t get to know you employer as much. i got into waterloo, chose uoft, cause its better, closer and well its in the heart of downtown, where waterloo well there is nothing much around. i am not saying uoft is way better, in some aspects it is and in some its not.

uoft #8th in world for engineering.
where waterloo is @ #27th

http://www.usnews.com/articles/education/worlds-best-universities/2010/02/25/worlds-best-universities-engineering-and-it.html
